highpower: Summer of 2012 when I was a camp counselor at the YMCA. Everyday I was in a role of power because I was looking after children and their well-being. I had to make certain judgment calls, and I had the power to tell a child what to do (if they didn't clean up after snack time or something to that effect). I had the power to write them up if they were being disrespectful, or to even talk to their parents at the end of the day. It wasn't so much that it was empowering but more of a rewarding job that carried prestige. The only reason it would be a powerful position is because you have not just one, but many lives in your hands, and that is how you have to think of it. You alone may see something another counselor couldn't which is why it is so important to really look after each child. Ultimately, we called the shots and controlled the outcome of many situations that could have possibly been bad. For example, the Y took a trip to the Eagles stadium. It is so huge an adult could probably have trouble if they got lost. We had to make sure that they stayed together at all times and nobody trailed off. It was hard and stressful, but when you're in that position, you remember your in charge, and if a child isn't listening to you, you always have a choice of what should be done. You take charge of a situation without being mean and they will respect you.  Sometimes, you even change lives  and that kid looks forward to seeing you everyday and next summer. It was a much more rewarding job than stressful.

lowpower: In some wrestling practices in high school, we had physical training sessions intended to increase strength and speed and mobility. It would be a Crossfit-style drill where all the wrestlers had to perform exercises for 5 minutes straight with 30 seconds of rest for an hour. Some of these exercises included going on the rowing machines, doing pull-ups, skipping with a 10-lb jumping rope, doing push-ups, climbing up and down 3 flights of stairs, and biking, all at high-intensity for 5 minutes each without stopping until our 30 second break, at which point the drill would continue. When I first did these workouts, it was extremely hard for me because I was not used to these high-intensity workouts. I often failed the expectations of my coach. For example, when my all my energy was spent and I could not continue with the pull-ups, he would come to me and start yelling at me to continue just like everyone else. He would be at my face until I got up on the pull-up bar and creaked one up, at which point he would go away to yell at someone else. He told me that even though I thought I wouldn't be able to complete the exercise, he said he would not let me stop. Even when I didn't stop but slowed my pace a little, he would come back and tell me to give my max effort. Sometimes all I wanted to do was drink water during the 5 minutes and he would stop me from doing and demand that I continue the exercise until the break. Initially I felt miserable and wanted to quit because all I wanted to do was be on the mat and wrestle, not do Crossfit, because wrestling was at least fun whereas depleting myself of energy wasn't.  But in some ways, him always being around and knowing that he was watching me really forced me to work hard and in the end it actually got me to a point where I adapted myself to enjoy his encouragements because it made me stronger and a better wrestler. I guess sometimes the end justifies the means.

highpower: Last year I was in Photojournalism at my high school. It was my first year in the class and one of my best friends was an editor of they yearbook and she convinced me to take the class. Around December I was taken off my original team and placed in charge of a different team who was having trouble. I had to approve the designs of spreads, the placement of picture, edit copy and text, manage the creation of graphics, decide who would cover events, what pictures where good pictures, who to get quotes from, what questions to ask people, the list goes on and on. I was in charge of 8 practically incompetent people, and when they did not do their job right it was my responsibility to fix it. I would stay after school until 9pm, skip my lunch breaks, etc just to get it done right. They would listen to what I told them but I guess it never processed right because, no matter how many times I explained exactly what I wanted, they would never get it right. My team members would listen to me freak out (and I mean yelling and cursing-one time I even cried) and my friends in the class would empathize, but they were going through almost the same thing. The faculty adviser and the editors knew that there was a problem with my team and they tried to help but couldn't. My friends would joke that I had become a dictator and on my paper plate award they used the hash-tag, #ameliaocracy. The final product of the yearbook was not worth the stress that probably took away years of my life. Its so cliche but with great power comes great responsibilities-and unless you have a great team, to get things right, you have to do everything yourself because its your ass on the line not theirs.

highpower: At the Sunday Children's Ministry at my church, I was a teenage volunteer who worked with Kindergarten through 4th grade children in leading them in fun worship songs with dance movements, learning memory verses, assisting the children's pastor in teaching the Bible lesson, and also asking Trivia questions about the lesson/story learned from the previous Sunday. As an incentive to pay attention to the lessons and participate in answering questions, I would reward correct answers to the Trivia questions with a single piece of candy the children could select from a variety in a box. My thoughts at each session were "I really hope the kids were paying attention last week, so we don't take more than 10-15 minutes to answer seven questions...". I was hopeful in wishing the kids to actually learn useful, important life lessons as well as enjoying the reward of candy and having fun, but at the same time, I was also used to them having no idea and simply guessing, giving general answers like, "Jesus!" or "God". I felt horrible when they gave the wrong answers, because I would have to reply, "Nope, sorry, that's not quite it", "Want to try again?" with no results. Despite feeling a little guilty when the kids were disappointed in getting the answer wrong (potential for embarrassment there, I suppose) and especially for not receiving candy, I understood that I was the teen leader and was a role model, and couldn't act "flaky" or "wishy-washy" with the kids and just give them the candy whenever they gave a off-the-mark answer. If they were rewarded every time they knowingly gave incorrect or incredibly vague answers, they would not benefit at all from the activity, and wouldn't come away from church having learned important lessons. I felt the position of power to be a slightly undesirable yet necessary role.
